04382nam a22006975i 9780691185347DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911853477 a10.1515/97806911853472doi  a(DE-B1597)501662  a(OCoLC)1076478236  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aE302.J442 1950a 7aBIO0070002bisacsh04a973.4/3/0921 aJefferson, Thomas, eauthor.10aPapers of Thomas Jefferson. n29, pThe Papers of Thomas Jefferson, Volume 29 ; 1 March 1796 to 31 December 1797 /cThomas Jefferson; Barbara B. Oberg. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPapers of Thomas Jefferson ;v2900tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tGUIDE TO EDITORIAL APPARATUS -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tVolume 29.1 March 1796 to 31 December 1797 -- tMARCH 1796 -- tAPRIL 1796 -- tMAY 1796 -- tJUNE 1796 -- tJULY 1796 -- tAUGUST 1796 -- tSEPTEMBER 1796 -- tOCTOBER 1796 -- tNOVEMBER 1796 -- tDECEMBER 1796 -- t1797 -- tJANUARY 1797 -- tFEBRUARY 1797 -- tMARCH 1797 -- tAPRIL 1797 -- tMAY 1797 -- tJUNE 1797 -- tJULY 1797 -- tAUGUST 1797 -- tSEPTEMBER 1797 -- tOCTOBER 1797 -- tNOVEMBER 1797 -- tDECEMBER 1797 -- tAppendix.Notations by Jefferson on Senate Documents -- tINDEX  aIn the twenty-two months covered by this volume, Jefferson spent most of his time at Monticello, where in his short-lived retirement from office he turned in earnest to the renovation of his residence and described himself as a ''monstrous farmer.'' Yet he narrowly missed being elected George Washington's successor as president and took the oath of office as vice president in March 1797. In early summer he presided over the Senate after President John Adams summoned Congress to deal with the country's worsening relations with France. As the key figure in the growing ''Republican quarter,'' Jefferson collaborated with such allies as James Monroe and James Madison and drafted a petition to the Virginia House of Delegates upholding the right of representatives to communicate freely with their constituents. The unauthorized publication of a letter to Philip Mazzei, in which Jefferson decried the former ''Samsons in the field and Solomons in the council'' who had been ''shorn by the harlot England,'' made the vice president the uncomfortable target of intense partisan attention. In addition, Luther Martin publicly challenged Jefferson's treatment, in Notes on Virginia, of the famous oration of Logan. Jefferson became president of the American Philosophical Society and presented a paper describing the fossilized remains of the megalonyx, or ''great claw.'' At Monticello he evaluated the merits of threshing machines, corresponded with British agricultural authorities, sought new crops for his rotation schemes, manufactured nails, and entertained family members and visitors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh1 aOberg, Barbara B., eeditor.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691185347zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691185347.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN